<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span></h2>
<div class="reflist columns references-column-count references-column-count-2" style="-moz-column-count: 2; -webkit-column-count: 2; column-count: 2; list-style-type: decimal;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-Adams-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Adams_1-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Adams_1-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Adams_1-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Maurianne Adams, Lee Anne Bell, Pat Griffin (2007). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=zgGUAgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA198"><i>Teaching for Diversity and Social Justice</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/Routledge" title="Routledge">Routledge</a>. pp.&#160;198–199. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1135928509" title="Special:BookSources/1135928509">1135928509</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 27,</span> 2014</span>. <q>Because of the complicated interplay among gender identity, gender roles, and sexual identity, transgender people are often assumed to be lesbian or gay (See <i>Overview: Sexism, Heterosexism, and Transgender Oppression</i>). ... Because transgender identity challenges a binary conception of sexuality and gender, educators must clarify their own understanding of these concepts. ... Facilitators must be able to help participants understand the connections among sexism, heterosexism, and transgender oppression and the ways in which gender roles are maintained, in part, through homophobia.</q></span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHomophobia&amp;rft.btitle=Teaching+for+Diversity+and+Social+Justice&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DzgGUAgAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA198&amp;rft.isbn=1135928509&amp;rft.pages=198-199&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Renzetti-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Renzetti_2-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Renzetti_2-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Claire M. Renzetti, Jeffrey L. Edleson (2008). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=lP1yAwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PT372"><i>Encyclopedia of Interpersonal Violence</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/SAGE_Publications" title="SAGE Publications" class="mw-redirect">SAGE Publications</a>. p.&#160;338. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1452265917" title="Special:BookSources/1452265917">1452265917</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 27,</span> 2014</span>. <q>In a culture of homophobia (an irrational fear of gay, lesbian, bisexual, and transgender [GLBT] people), GLBT people often face a heightened risk of violence specific to their sexual identities.</q></span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHomophobia&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopedia+of+Interpersonal+Violence&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DlP1yAwAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPT372&amp;rft.isbn=1452265917&amp;rft.pages=338&amp;rft.pub=SAGE+Publications&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Schuiling-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Schuiling_3-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Schuiling_3-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Kerri Durnell Schuiling, Frances E. Likis (2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=pj_ourS3PBMC&amp;pg=PA186"><i>Women's Gynecologic Health</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/Jones_%26_Bartlett_Publishers" title="Jones &amp; Bartlett Publishers" class="mw-redirect">Jones &amp; Bartlett Publishers</a>. pp.&#160;187–188. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0763756377" title="Special:BookSources/0763756377">0763756377</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 27,</span> 2014</span>. <q>Homophobia is an individual's irrational fear or hate of homosexual people. This may include bisexual or transgender persons, but sometimes the more distinct terms of biphobia or transphobia, respectively, are used.</q></span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHomophobia&amp;rft.btitle=Women%27s+Gynecologic+Health&amp;rft.date=2011&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dpj_ourS3PBMC%26pg%3DPA186&amp;rft.isbn=0763756377&amp;rft.pages=187-188&amp;rft.pub=Jones+%26+Bartlett+Publishers&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
