<li id="cite_note-Spijkerboer-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Spijkerboer_5-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Thomas Spijkerboer (2013). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=oOxBtViD0KcC&amp;pg=PA122"><i>Fleeing Homophobia: Sexual Orientation, Gender Identity and Asylum</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/Routledge" title="Routledge">Routledge</a>. p.&#160;122. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1134098359" title="Special:BookSources/1134098359">1134098359</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">December 27,</span> 2014</span>. <q>Transgender people subjected to violence, in a range of cultural contexts, frequently report that transphobic violence is expressed in homophobic terms. The tendency to translate violence against a trans person to homophobia reflects the role of gender in attribution of homosexuality as well as the fact that hostility connected to homosexuality is often associated with the perpetrators' prejudices about particular gender practices and their visibility.</q></span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHomophobia&amp;rft.aulast=Thomas+Spijkerboer&amp;rft.au=Thomas+Spijkerboer&amp;rft.btitle=Fleeing+Homophobia%3A+Sexual+Orientation%2C+Gender+Identity+and+Asylum&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DoOxBtViD0KcC%26pg%3DPA122&amp;rft.isbn=1134098359&amp;rft.pages=122&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
